    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-10-18T11:52:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-10-18T11:52:00-05:00" n="139"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d139">
                <head>139. Telegram From <gloss type="from">the Embassy in France</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d139fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> 3 <gloss
                            target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>. Confidential; Priority. Repeated to <gloss
                            target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss> and Panama City.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Paris</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1972-10-18T16:52:00+00:00">October 18, 1972,
                        1652Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19905. Subject: <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> Meeting in Panama. Ref: Paris
                        19729.<note n="2" xml:id="d139fn2">Telegram 19729 from Paris, October 17,
                        described an earlier meeting in which the same points were made.
                        (Ibid.)</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>In conversation October 18 on unrelated subjects, Quai Director American
                        Affairs told PolCouns that instructions on possible <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                            >SC</gloss>
                        <pb facs="0301" n="264" xml:id="pg_264"/> meeting in Panama were sent to
                        French Embassy Washington on October 17.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Essence of message to French Embassy is: <list>
                            <label>A)</label>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_SM1">Schumann</persName> feels he cannot reneg
                                on his commitment to Latin Americans to support Latin American
                                initiative to hold <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> meeting in
                                Panama. (French working level had not briefed <persName
                                    corresp="#p_SM1">Schumann</persName> on possible <gloss
                                    target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> meeting in Panama prior to his
                                September dinner with Latin Americans since “idea had been
                                germinating for about eight months and US reps had not made a
                                particular issue of it.”)</item>
                            <label>B)</label>
                            <item>Ever since Ambassador’s representation to <persName
                                    corresp="#p_SM1">Schumann</persName> on October 5 (Paris
                                    18969),<note n="3" xml:id="d139fn3">
                                    <ref target="#d133">Document 133</ref>.</note> French reps in
                                New York and elsewhere have been under strict instructions not to
                                “proselytize” on behalf of Panamanian proposal. French will continue
                                to maintain this “discreet” position.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>PolCouns commented that while he could appreciate <gloss
                            target="#t_FONMIN1">FonMin</gloss>’s’ difficulty in reneging on his
                        commitment to Latin Americans, something more than apparent neutrality of
                        French position was needed in the circumstances. Speaking personally,
                        PolCouns asked Quai Director whether he could consider instructing French
                        reps, without reneging on <persName corresp="#p_SM1">Schumann</persName>’s
                        promise, to attempt persuade Latin Americans of wisdom in the circumstances
                        of not pressing issue to a vote. Without committing himself, Quai Director
                        said he would look into this possibility.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WAK1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Watson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
